{[%evp 0,29,21,18,18,-11,47,7,-6,-8,10,20,57,63,42,36,11,53,40,7,32,32,19,-23,
-14,-32,-27,-15,69,-36,23,-24]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 $5 {I have started
analysing this time a long time ago. At some point, I came across computer
games where the engines played h2-h4 on move 3 on regular basis. Even though I
was sceptical, I started to work on this idea. I need to point out that 6-7
years ago, the engines were not such authority as nowadays. Later, in 2016, I
saw Anton Korobov playing this line against Rinat Jumabayev. Thanks to this
game, my enthusiasm for this line returned. Even though Anton lost this game,
in the same year, Topalov played 3.h4 at Candidates Tournament against Anish
Giri. The game ended in a draw since Topalov failed to prove an edge in the
opening. In the next three years, this variation disappeared from the practice
of the strongest chess players and quite recently, in 2019, one of the
well-known innovators of modern chess Alexander Grischuk began to play this
line on a fairly permanent basis with varying success. However, he brought a
large number of new ideas and many people picked up after him, including
Magnus Carlsen. In general, this line became quite popular. In my opinion,
there is  room for new ideas and concepts in this still relatively less
explored line. Modern practice shows that players of all levels can play 3.h4
with both colours. Almost all the lines lead to a full-blooded game where it's
slightly easier to play with White. One of the main points behind 3.h4 is to
prevent Black from obtaining a favourable version of the Gruenfeld. There is
an additional factor that contributes to the rising popularity of the entire
concept with h2-h4. The new generation of neural network-based engines made us
reconsider the advance of the rook pawn in almost every position. For example,
in the games of Alpha Zero, we can often see the h-pawn going all the way to
h6 at an early stage of the game. Besides restricting the opponent's pieces
and providing space in the middlegame, this pawn is a tremendous asset in
every endgame. In the current database, you will see this concept on multiple
occasions. Black can get a decent version of Benko, Benoni or King's Indian in
this line but it's not easy to find a proper moment for Gruenfeld style play
with ...d7-d5. In this chapter, I tried to cover Gruenfeld style attempts for
Black} Bg7 ({An obvious question is what happens if Black radically prevents
the march of the h-pawn by means of} 3... h5 {We are going to examine the
advance ...h7-h5 in connection of different setups for Black. For the time
being, we will focus on the Gruenfeld setup where the inclusion of the moves
h2-h4 and ...h7-h5 works in White's favour. Black's main problem is that after}
4. Nc3 d5 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. Bg5 $5 {the g5-bishop is very stable. In Gruenfeld,
Black often gains tempi by using the vulnerable position of this bishop. For
example, now the typical idea of ...Ne4 is less effective.} dxc4 {[%cal Gc7c5]
The most principled reaction. Black is planning to attack the centre by means
of ...c7-c5.} ({Playing in the Schlechter style with} 6... c6 $6 {does not
work well. White's most practical choice is} 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. e3 $14 {With a
bishop on g7, the Slav Exchange structure is favourable for White. Black's
dark-squared bishop is restricted by White's central pawn chain. Additionally,
being on g7, the bishop does not have control of the queenside where White is
planning to play. A possible scheme would be Be2, 0-0, Qb3, Na4-c5, and Rac1.
The fortified g5-bishop is also very annoying.}) ({The main drawback of the
inclusion h2-h4 and ...h7-h5 is seen in the line} 6... Ne4 $6 7. cxd5 {when
Black should probably play} Nxc3 ({The problem is that after} 7... Nxg5 8. Nxg5
$16 {the typical ...e7-e6 does not work since the g5-knight is protected.}) 8.
bxc3 Qxd5 9. e3 c5 10. Be2 cxd4 11. cxd4 {We have reached a thematic Gruenfeld
structure. If Black does not manage to quickly create counterplay, White has
an advantage due to his better central control and the possibility of quickly
occupying the c-file. Once again, the g5-bishop disrupts Black's coordination.
With the move h2-h4 included, the typical attempt to release the pressure} Qa5+
{can be answered with} 12. Nd2 $1 $16 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd2c4,Ge2f3,Ga1c1] Since
the bishop is not hanging, White is not forced to exchange the queens. White's
next moves will be 0-0 followed by Nc4, Bf3, and Rc1, developing a very strong
initiative.} ({The endgame arising after} 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 $14 {is still
slightly better for White. His main idea is to invade via the c-file. Due to
the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5, Black does not have a
comfortable way of kicking the g5-bishop back. 1-0 (42) Eynullayev, A (2290)
-Wang, S (2122) Abu Dhabi 2019})) 7. e4 c5 8. d5 {The most ambitious
continuation.} ({The alternative} 8. Bxc4 $5 {is possible as well. White still
retains some advantage.}) 8... b5 9. e5 {This position looks very dangerous
for Black. Even though not completely forced, the following variation is quite
illustrative -} Nh7 {The precise defence.} ({After} 9... b4 10. Na4 Nxd5 11.
Bxc4 Nb6 12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 13. Bb3 $36 {White has dangerous initiative in this
queenless middlegame. Black has to take care of his vulnerable king and poor
