{[%evp 0,37,27,32,19,0,36,2,18,10,18,9,15,15,13,9,4,2,6,13,22,19,26,24,18,41,
42,42,21,-2,-10,-16,-9,-31,13,-13,-16,0,-8,-7]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 c6 {
Playing the Schlechter Variation is always a sound and valid option. Generally
speaking, however, even the classical version of this system tends to be a bit
passive. As we are going to witness in this chapter, the inclusion of the move
h2-h4 gives White additional possibilities.} 4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Bf4 {
In my opinion, when Black develops his bishop on g7, entering the Slav
Exchange structure is always a good option for White. As pointed out in the
comments to the previous chapter, Black's dark-squared bishop cannot take part
in the queenside actions.} Bg7 ({Another possible move order is} 6... Nc6 7. e3
{And here, instead of the usual 7...Bg7 which will transpose to the main line,
Black has an active independent option -} Ne4 {In my opinion, however, this
knight jump is a bit premature.} 8. Nf3 {The most natural continuation. Before
going for concrete actions, White wants to complete the development.} ({
A recent game saw} 8. Qb3 {which, in my opinion, is not necessary. After} Nxc3
9. bxc3 Bg7 10. h5 O-O 11. hxg6 hxg6 $132 {Black was doing fine since White
still needs to complete the development. 1-0 (24) Kapnisis, S (2471) -Teclaf,P
(2440) Prague 2020}) 8... Bg7 9. h5 Nxc3 10. bxc3 {This is a pawn structure
that we are going to face on multiple occasions. The weakness of the c3-pawn
is by no means one-sided. In return, White gets the semi-open b-file for his
rook as well as the possibility to strike in the centre with c3-c4.
Additionally, since the d4-pawn is already protected, White can often execute
the advance e3-e4. It's important to point out that on the kingside White
usually plays h5-h6 in order to gain space and restrict the activity of the
black pieces. Black has two typical ways of creating counterplay - pressure
along the c-file, and executing the advance ... e7-e5. In general, however,
the arising positions remain more pleasant for White.} O-O 11. Rb1 $36 {
Remember this thematic move. The pressure along the b-file is very annoying.}
Bg4 {In my opinion, this is the most precise move. Black leaves the b7-pawn in
order to fight for an initiative.} ({A very instructive mistake is} 11... b6 {
when after} 12. Bb5 {White immediately attacks the vulnerable knight, thus
winning the fight for the key e5-square. After} Na5 13. hxg6 hxg6 14. Ne5 $16 {
[%cal Gd1f3] White has a huge advantage. The queen will soon join the attack
via the f3-square.}) 12. h6 {Since opening the h-file does not provide any
advantage, White uses the second thematic device.} Bf6 13. Rxb7 {In this
position, the critical is} e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Be2 Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 Bxc3+ 17.
Kf1 Be6 18. a4 $14 {Definitely, White is the one having a more pleasant
position in view of his more active pieces. The h6-pawn makes the black king
potentially vulnerable whereas the white king is pretty safe on f1.}) 7. e3 Nc6
8. Be2 {[%cal Gh4h5] It is important to start with this move. White prepares
the thematic h4-h5.} O-O {Allowing h4-h5 is Black's most precise reaction.} ({
The attempt to prevent h4-h5 with} 8... h5 $6 {leads to favourable for White
positions. After} 9. Nf3 {[%csl Gf4] we can see the difference in the activity
of the dark-squared bishops. With the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ...
h7-h5, Black can never harass the f4-bishop with ... Nh5. Note that in the
classical Schlechter, White's dark-squared bishop is usually behind the pawn
chain (mostly on d2).} O-O 10. O-O ({Having normal development, White can
afford} 10. Qb3 $5 {Black should probably answer with} Na5 ({Once again, the
move} 10... b6 $6 {does not work well since it creates queenside weaknesses.
In the game that we are following, White played} 11. Rc1 Bb7 12. O-O Ne4 $2 {
This is already a mistake. After} 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Ng5 Na5 15. Qa4 $18 {
White had a winning advantage in the game 1/2-1/2 (61) Harsha, B  (2509)
-Rathanvel,V (2438) Mosonmagyarovar 2021. The direct threat is b2-b4.}) 11. Qa3
Bg4 12. Rc1 e6 13. Bg5 $14 {White is slightly better in view of his better
piece coordination. Black is under annoying pressure.}) 10... Ne4 {As usual,
this knight jump is the cornerstone of Black's counterplay in this pawn
structure.} ({After} 10... Bg4 {the typical reaction is} 11. Qb3 {Always have
in mind this queen move when the bishop leaves the queenside. After} Na5 12.
Qb5 a6 13. Qb4 $14 {the b4-queen exerts a lot of pressure. All white pieces,
except the f3-knight, are taking part in the queenside battle. At the same
time, Black's minor pieces are not coordinated at all.}) 11. Rc1 {[%csl Gg7]
The most typical reaction.} ({There is nothing wrong with} 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12.
Ng5 Bf5 13. Qb3 $14 {when White retains his advantage.}) 11... Nxc3 {In this
position, both} 12. Rxc3 $14 {[%cal Gd1a4,Gf1c1]} ({and} 12. bxc3 {[%cal Gc3c4]
are possible})) ({The move} 8... h6 $6 {was played by Nepomniachtchi in his
game against Grischuk. Obviously, the idea is to enable . ..g6-g5 after h4-h5.
On the downside, besides being a waste of time, this move makes the kingside
