1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 c5 4. d5 {The Benko Gambit is one of the soundest
responses to 3.h4. Nevertheless, as we are going to see, the advance of the
rook's pawn often fits into White's entire concept. My analysis shows that
it's not easy for Black to obtain full compensation for the pawn.} b5 $5 ({
The continuation} 4... e6 5. dxe6 dxe6 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nc3 Bg7 {will
transpose to Chapter 6.}) 5. cxb5 a6 6. e3 {In my opinion, this is White's
most challenging option. Instead of contributing to Black's queenside
development, White first tries to establish a firm control of the b5-square.
Even against the Classical Benko, White's best system is 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5
b5 4.cxb5 a6 5.e3. This line was extensively covered in the excellent database
of GM Grigor Grigorov - Modern Repertoire against the Benko.} ({In Korobov's
game I mentioned in Chapter 1, Anton played} 6. bxa6 {which is not the best
choice as White is behind in development. His last move only speeds up Black's
development. The game continued} Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O (7... Bxa6 $5 $132) 8. e4 e6 $1
9. dxe6 fxe6 10. Bg5 Qa5 11. Qd2 Nc6 $36 {Black enjoyed an excellent
counterplay in the game 0-1 (23) Korobov, A (2713)-Jumabayev, R (2607) Moscow
2016}) 6... Bg7 {The most natural option.} ({An important alternative is} 6...
axb5 $6 7. Bxb5 Qa5+ 8. Nc3 Ne4 {Black is putting tremendous pressure on c3.
White, however, can stabilize the position with the precise} 9. Nge2 $1 ({
Worse is} 9. Bd2 {when after} Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Bg7 11. Nge2 Ba6 $44 {Black
enjoyed a decent counterplay in the game 0-1 (42) Hasseine, M (2157)-Kirk, E  
(2447) Playchess.com INT 2021. White will not be able to hold the blockade on
b5. Additionally, the strong g7-bishop has no opponent.}) 9... Bg7 10. a4 $16 {
White has a stable advantage. Establishing a blockade on b5 is one of the most
powerful strategies against Black's queenside play. In order to regain the
pawn, Black will be forced to part with his powerful g7-bishop.}) 7. Nc3 O-O ({
Once again, putting pressure on c3 is not the best strategy. For example, after
} 7... axb5 8. Bxb5 Qa5 9. a4 Ne4 {White plays the thematic} 10. Nge2 Ba6 {
Black tries to remove the blockade by using the unprotected a1-rook. White's
typical antidote is} 11. Ra3 $1 {restricting Black's entire counterplay.} ({
After} 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. O-O Nxc3 13. bxc3 $14 {Black has good chances to
fight for a draw in view of White's weakened queenside structure. Eventually,
Black even managed to win in the game 0-1 (61) Bluebaum, M (2640) -Moroni, L  
(2575) Chess.com INT 2021}) 11... O-O 12. O-O Nf6 13. e4 $16 {White enjoys a
healthy extra pawn.}) 8. a4 Bb7 {A very principled approach. Black is planning
