{[%evp 0,21,27,25,32,0,37,-2,-12,2,16,21,23,13,28,15,54,22,23,28,100,55,59,33]
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 (3... d6 {Black can choose a setup with quick
Nbd7 without castles, but I believe that White has an edge in this line.} 4.
Nc3 Nbd7 5. e4 e5 6. d5 Nc5 {This idea is well known in KID, Black puts
pressure on e4, before castling. I think it is important for White to delay
the move f3, which weakens the dark squares and closes the d1-h5 diagonal. In
general, in this structure, the move h2-h4 is quite useful.} 7. Qc2 a5 {
in this King's Indian structure White has a very decent chance to fight for an
advantage as h4 is normally sound addition} 8. Be2 ({Another setup is} 8. g3 $5
$146 h5 (8... c6 {Black should complete the development before opening the
centre.} 9. Be3 a4 {is logical with the idea Qa5, but White has a strong reply
at his disposal} (9... Qb6 {is well met by} 10. f3 a4 11. g4 $14 {White's
initiative on the kingside is more dangerous than Black's on the queenside.
Now the advance h4-h5 will be very unpleasant.}) 10. Bxc5 $1 (10. f3 Qa5 $132)
10... dxc5 11. Rd1 cxd5 12. cxd5 Bd6 13. Nf3 $14 {The position is quite
unusual, but I prefer White here. Black's bishop pair is not a very
significant factor. Black's king is weak and the idea h4-h5 is always in the
air, but also White can try to play on the queenside. The -a pawn needs
protection and there are a lot of weak squares in Black's camp. If White
manages to exchange the light-squared bishops, then the position will be close
to strategically winning}) 9. f3 c6 10. Nh3 $1 {Typical idea in Saemish
structures, the knight is very well placed on "f2"} a4 11. Nf2 cxd5 12. cxd5
Bd7 13. Nd3 {I like the idea to exchange the strong c5-knight} Nxd3+ 14. Bxd3
Bh6 (14... Qa5 {is possible, but then Black can't exchange the dark-squared
bishops after} 15. Bg5 Bg7 16. a3 $14) 15. Bxh6 Rxh6 16. a3 $14 {The position
is double-edged, but I like that White has a space advantage, the -a4 pawn is
weak.}) 8... h5 {This move was Giri's choice and It makes a lot of sense} 9.
Nf3 Bg4 (9... Ng4 $132 {[%cal Gf8h6] this looks like a logical improvement} 10.
Ng5 {with an interesting fight}) 10. Be3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 $14 {Black should
probably go for the Bh6 exchange sooner or later, but I don't think that this
will fully solve his problems. White can choose on which side of the board to
play. It is possible to prepare a long castle and open the centre and the
kingside. A more positional option is to play g3, 0-0 and advance his
queenside pawns. 0-1 (39) Fedoseev,V (2677)-Giri,A (2769) Moscow 2019}) 4. Nc3
{now Black can try} Nc6 $5 {here or after d6. I think Nc6 first is a bit more
flexible} (4... d6 5. e4 Nc6 6. Nge2 $1 {This is not possible with the 4.. .
Nc6 move order. White's knight is very well placed here, leaving the -f3
square for the pawn. I also prefer to keep my options in the centre more
flexible} (6. Be2 $6 {is not very accurate here, because it gives Black's
knight access to the -d4 square} e5 $1 7. d5 Nd4 8. Nf3 Nxe2 $1 (8... c5 {
is wrong and White is better after:} 9. dxc6 Nxc6 10. Bg5 $14 {0-1 (31)
Khismatullin, D (2611) -Samusenko,M (2445) Sochi 2019}) 9. Qxe2 Bg4 $15 {
Black's position is already preferable}) (6. d5 {was tried in a recent
high-level game, but I don't think that it gives an advantage} Ne5 {with a
pawn still on h2, the advance f2-f4 will be very strong, but now this will
weaken "g4" too much.} 7. Be2 h5 8. Bf4 O-O 9. Nf3 Nxf3+ 10. gxf3 {This is an
interesting concept that we will see later in the database.} c6 $132 {The
position is with mutual chances, but Black won a fantastic game in 0-1  (41)
Fedoseev,V (2696)-Carlsen,M (2847) Krasnaya Polyana 2021}) 6... O-O (6... Nh5
$5 {MVL tried hyper-modern attempt to fight for the center, but I still prefer
White's position after:} 7. Bg5 $1 {This tricky move stops e5 and tries to
provoke the advance h7-h6, which will weaken Black's position} (7. f3 {will be
meeting with} e5 $1 $13) 7... O-O 8. Qd2 f6 9. Be3 f5 10. O-O-O $1 (10. exf5 $6
{is Grischuk's choice, but I think it is wrong} Bxf5 11. f3 e5 12. d5 Na5 $1 {
is my improvement. This move provokes b2-b3 which weakens dark squares a lot} (
{the game continues} 12... Nd4 $6 {and now the simple} 13. Nxd4 {gives White
an advantage} (13. O-O-O Nxe2+ 14. Nxe2 e4 $15 {1-0 (49) Grischuk, A (2766)
-Vachier Lagrave,M (2775) Paris 2019}) 13... exd4 14. Bxd4 $14) 13. b3 e4 $36 {
The position looks very strange with both Black's knights on the edge of the
board, but I think that Black gets his typical King's Indian counterplay.
White's king has no safe spot on the board and different tactics are possible.}
) 10... e5 11. d5 Ne7 12. f3 {We achieve a Saemish position with White's king
