$13 {The engines are probably holding this, but it looks a bit scary and the
absence of the g7 bishop}) 11... Re8 12. hxg6 hxg6 13. Kf1 Ndf6 14. g3 Bf5 15.
Bf4 Qd7 16. Rh4 $132) 11. Qc2 $5 {is a decent attempt to get a complex
playable position} (11. Bg5 {this move is almost always met with} Bxc3+ 12.
bxc3 f6 13. Bd2 {Ding played reasonably and posed some practical troubles.
Although it seems like Black is doing OK after Nde5 here or after g5} g5 $5 (
13... Nde5 $1 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. hxg6 Bf5 $5 16. Qa4+ Kd8 17. O-O-O Kc7 $132)
14. O-O Nde5 $1 (14... Nge5 $2 15. Nd4 $16 {0.08;-0.07: '->!': 1/2 (88)-1/2 
(88) Ding,L (2805) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2767) Ekaterinburg 2021}) 15. Nd4 (15.
Qc2 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 O-O 17. Rae1 Qf7 18. Qb1 b6 $132 {With a Black's king safe
on g8, White doesn't have much compensation for the weekend structure on the
queenside.}) (15. Nxe5 {is another try, which doesn't give White an advantage}
Nxe5 16. h6 Bd7 17. Bh5+ {This check is pointless because Black's king is
feeling very well on the queenside..} Kd8 18. f4 gxf4 19. Bxf4 Kc7 $132 {
Black's king is quite safe and now, after Rg8, Black will take the initiative.}
) 15... O-O $13 {Black's position is quite safe, in the worst case, the knight
will go back to h6}) ({After} 11. Ng5 {Black will play in the same way as
after 11.Bg5} Bxc3+ $1 12. bxc3 gxh5 $132) (11. Bf4 Nde5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Bxe5
Nxe5 {The important rule in Benoni's structure is that If Black manages to
exchange two minor pieces, his position is quite good.} 14. Qd2 g5 15. O-O-O
Bd7 $132) (11. O-O {This looks too soft and now it seems that h4-h5 was just a
waste of time} O-O 12. hxg6 fxg6 $1 {I like this approach because now Black
can put a pawn on h6, to cover g5 and also the rook is quite active on the
semi-open f-file.} 13. Bg5 Ndf6 $132 14. Qc2 h6 15. Bxf6 (15. Bd2 Bf5 $132)
15... Qxf6 16. Rae1 g5 17. Bd3 Bd7 $132) 11... Nde5 $1 (11... O-O {is still
premature and White is better after:} 12. Bg5 Bf6 13. Qd2 $14) 12. h6 Bf6 13.
Ne4 {Strategically Whites position should be preferred due to the bishop pair
and h6 pawn, but Black has some dynamical counterchances} (13. Kf1 Bf5 14. Qa4+
Kd8 (14... Kf8 15. Bd2 $14) 15. Bd2 Re8 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Qb3 Kc7 $132) 13...
Bf5 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 15. Qa4+ Kf8 $1 $13 {This time Black king should go to the
kingside because of the lack of defenders on the queenside.} (15... Kd8 $2 16.
O-O Kc7 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. b4 $16 {and soon Black's king will start feeling
uncomfortable.}) 16. O-O Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Ne5 18. Be2 g5 $1 {This is the point
of Black's play. Now the h6-pawn is lost and Black can even start thinking of
organizing an attack against White's king. Of course, White will try to open
the position somehow using f4 or b4 breaks.} 19. b4 b6 $13 {The position still
looks promising for White, but objectively speaking, Black has reasonable
counterplay.} *

