{[%evp 0,39,25,25,19,-11,36,2,2,2,-4,-3,12,12,14,9,32,31,86,25,33,36,35,-2,-2,
-2,14,11,2,-2,14,-24,31,23,23,23,18,12,27,32,24,12]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 ({Black rarely choose this move order} 4... O-O {maybe because
there is an extra attempt} 5. h5 $5 $146 {Nobody played it yet but it seems
that there is decent room for analysis.} Nxh5 6. e4 (6. g4 {transposes to the
mainline after:} Nf6 7. e4 d6) 6... d6 (6... e5 $5) 7. g4 Nf6 8. g5 Ne8 (8...
Nfd7 {This is an interesting idea. Black has passive pieces, but he is a pawn
up and the main idea is Re8-Nf8 followed by e6} 9. f4 Re8 10. Be3 c5 11. d5 Nf8
(11... b5 $5 {Playing in the Benko style is also possible here}) 12. Qd2 (12.
Bd3 b5 $1 13. cxb5 Nbd7 14. Nge2 ({if White develops the knight on f3 then e6
is just powerful} 14. Nf3 e6 $15) 14... a6 $132 {again White is overextended
and after a6 and e6, the position will open and Black will have at least equal
chances}) 12... e6 $5 (12... e5 {is possible too, but White can sacrifice a
second pawn with} 13. f5 $1 gxf5 14. Qh2 f4 15. Bf2 $44 {The position is close
and Black doesn't have any counterplay. In the meantime, the maneuver
Nf3-h4-f5 looks quite unplesant}) 13. Bd3 b5 14. Nxb5 exd5 15. cxd5 Na6 $132 {
Black will continue with Nb4-Rb8, Bf5. It is some kind of dynamic equality}) (
8... Nh5 $2 9. Be2 $18) 9. f4 c5 10. d5 {From e8, the knight is not blocking
the light-square bishop and Black will continue with f5 or e6 breaks} e6 (10...
f5 {this looks too risky after:} 11. gxf6 Nxf6 12. Nf3 Qe8 13. Ng5 $44 {
with the idea Ne6 next. I believe White's play is much easier.}) 11. Bd2 exd5
12. cxd5 f5 {Black needs to play active. Otherwise, Qe2-h2 will come with a
devastating attack} 13. Qe2 fxe4 14. Qh2 $44 {I decided to stop here, but you
can analyze this even more. The h7-pawn is lost, but it is not the end of the
world. Black's king will be safe on f7 for the time being. We can conclude
that it looks quite dangerous for Black, but the game is still on.}) 5. e4 O-O
6. Be2 c5 {back in time I considered this as the main response to 3.h4. Now
I'm unsure because arising positions are not without danger for Black which is
also proved by statistic} (6... e5 {entering King's Indian structure is wrong.
In this case, the pawn on h4 is just perfectly placed and ready to move
forward.} 7. d5 Na6 8. g4 (8. h5 {this is another option for us and it looks
equally good as 8.g4} Nc5 9. h6 {This is an interesting strategical decision.
With the pawn on h6, the advance f7-f5 is not that good for Black and White
can simply put a piece on g5 and then continue with his typical queenside play.
} Bh8 10. Qc2 $14) 8... Nc5 9. f3 a5 10. Nh3 c6 11. h5 $16 {The advantage is
close to decisive. Usually in KID Black is aiming for Kingside play and White
is playing on the queenside. In this case, White has an advantage on both
flangs.}) (6... Nc6 {Nc6 here is wrong because White is simply better after:}
7. d5 Ne5 8. h5 $14) 7. d5 e6 $1 {Benoni setup is the most reliable one} (7...
b5 {this is not the best version of Benko since White managed to push e4 and
is now ready to secure b5 square} 8. cxb5 a6 9. a4 axb5 10. Bxb5 Ba6 11. Bd2
Bxb5 12. axb5 Nbd7 13. Nf3 $14 {Of course, Black has some compensation, but in
my opinion, not enough for full equality 1-0 (31) Vachier Lagrave,M (2751)
-Svidler,P (2714) Saint Louis 2021}) 8. h5 {White needs to justify his early
h4 move} exd5 9. exd5 (9. cxd5 {As a rule in this variation. The most common
Benoni structure after cxd5 is in Black's favour because the h4 advance is not
very useful and sometimes is just a waste of time. As we can see in the
analysis, Black obtains decent counterplay after:} b5 $5 (9... Re8 $5 {The
Standart counterplay in the centre is possible too} 10. hxg6 (10. h6 {is
possible here too, but Black is just fine. He has enough counterplay in the
centre and on the queenside.} Bh8) 10... fxg6 11. Qc2 a6 12. a4 Nbd7 $132 {
Black is fully developed. Ne5 is coming soon and I can't see how White can use
the semi-open h-file.}) 10. e5 {after any other move. Black just achive a
wonderful Benoni} dxe5 11. h6 Bh8 12. Bxb5 Ne8 {[%cal Re8d6]} 13. Nh3 Nd6 $132
{The position is quite interesting, but it is obvious that Black has a good
chances. e5-e4 will come soon, Qb6 is another idea.}) 9... Re8 10. h6 $1 {
[%csl Gg7,Gh6] the same idea to secure h6-pawn} (10. hxg6 {is again well met by
} fxg6 11. Nf3 Nbd7 $132) 10... Bh8 11. Bg5 (11. Kf1 {is too slow and Black
has a good game after:} Ne4 $132) 11... Qb6 $1 (11... Bf5 $2 {failed to
equalize} 12. f3 Bd7 13. Kf1 $16 {[%cal Rd1d2,Rd2f4]}) (11... Nbd7 12. Nf3 Qb6
13. Qd2 $14) (11... a6 {is again too slow} 12. Kf1 $5 b5 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Bxb5
$14 {and Black doesn't have enough compensation for the sacrificing material})
12. b3 $1 {It seems that White can weaken the dark-squares. I can't find how
Black can gain some benefits from it.} Ne4 {Black tried a few other options
but it seems like White has a promising position} (12... Qa5 13. Bd2 (13. Qd2 {
will be met by} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] and Black has decent counterplay}) 13... Qd8 (
13... Nbd7 {after this White will continue with Kf1, Rc1}) 14. Kf1 Ne4 15. Nxe4
Rxe4 16. Rc1 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gg2g4,Gf1g2,Gf2f4,Gd2c3]} Rh4 {[%csl Gh6]} (16... Nd7
17. g3 Re8 18. Kg2 $14) 17. Rxh4 Qxh4 18. g3 Qd8 19. Kg2 $14 {The position
calms down and White has an advantage. White has more space on both flangs.
The d6-pawn is potentially weak and Black's pieces lack good squares. 1/2 (39)
Grischuk,A (2766) -Vachier Lagrave, M (2775) Paris 2019}) (12... Bf5 {with the
idea Ne4} 13. Kf1 Ne4 {this is the most straightforward continuation} (13...
Na6 14. Rc1 (14. a3 $1 $14 Ne4 15. Nxe4 Rxe4 16. Ra2 {[%cal Ra2d2]}) 14... Ne4
15. Nxe4 Rxe4 16. Rh4 Rxh4 17. Bxh4 $14 {1/2-1/2 (30) Kantor,G (2527)-Ganguly,
S (2625) Biel 2021}) 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Rc1 Qa5 (15... Na6 16. Rh3 Qa5 17. g4 $1
{and Black's bishop is trapped} Nb4 18. f3 Nxa2 19. fxe4 Nxc1 20. Bxc1 $16) 16.
a4 Na6 17. Bd3 Bxd3+ 18. Qxd3 Nb4 19. Qf3 $40 {Black's pieces on the queenside
are not doing much. In the meantime, White has some initiative on the kingside
and wants to complete the development with Ne2, g3, Kg2.}) 13. Nxe4 Rxe4 14.
Kf1 $5 ({First I was concentrated to} 14. Rc1 {and I found that after} Na6 $1 {
it's a more or less forced draw, but Black needs to find a long sequence of
only moves} 15. Rh4 (15. Nf3 {doesn't promise much after:} Qa5+ 16. Qd2 Nb4 17.
